snippet.textDisplay:
Just by doing some research, his swimming was within allowed rules. The head needs to be above water at all times. So no front crawl is allowed like some commentators mentioned. I believe that the water-polo crawl style where the head is above water could be allowed but its pretty hard for someone who doesn't train it.
You cant lose form with push ups, if you do, you're out.
Sit ups need to be done with elbows touching the knees or a couple inches lower than that. He went above that every time so pretty good.
And pull ups, you cant let go of the bar at any point or you're out.
Running is self explanatory, just beat the minimum time :) not on a treadmill tho, because not the same muscles are engaged as running around in the heat and a hard surface.
Feel free to correct me if I said something wrong. I'm still damn impressed with how well he did as it is.

snippet.textDisplay: First off I’d like to send my respect, but I cannot help but state that he failed every test due to the test regulations. He failed the swim by stopping and switching to freestyle (the 500yd swim is to be done using breaststroke or sidestroke continuously), he failed the push-ups by the lack of reps and him raising his butt in the rest position, he failed the sit-ups by raising his butt in order to achieve more reps (which terminates his test at that moment) which left his total below 50, he failed the pull ups by kicking to get up and by leaving the bar (another critique is that there is no time limit on the pull ups), and he failed the run by not completing the 1.5 miles. Again I have nothing but respect, completing these exercises in the allotted time is extremely difficult which is why the SEALs is such a prestigious division of the US Navy.
